{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505900"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2495"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2495"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.08,0.05,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42508"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a pruritic, erythematous eruption across her abdomen. She is 30 weeks pregnant with twins. This is her first pregnancy. She denies any previous medical history, including skin disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a dermatosis of pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pemphigoid gestationis","Cutaneous lupus erythematosus","Psoriasis","Lichen planus","Hidradenitis suppurativa"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPemphigoid gestationis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare autoimmune blistering disorder that occurs during pregnancy, typically presenting in the second or third trimester. It is characterised by intensely pruritic, erythematous papules and plaques that can progress to form blisters. The condition is associated with the presence of autoantibodies against the basement membrane zone of the skin. It is one of the specific dermatoses of pregnancy and can recur in subsequent pregnancies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune condition that can affect the skin, but it is not specific to pregnancy. While pregnancy can exacerbate lupus symptoms, it is not classified as a dermatosis of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterised by well-demarcated, scaly plaques. It is not specific to pregnancy, and in fact, many women experience an improvement in their psoriasis symptoms during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen planus\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic inflammatory condition that affects the skin and mucous membranes. It is not specific to pregnancy and does not typically present as a dermatosis of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHidradenitis suppurativa\u003C/strong\u003E is a chronic skin condition involving recurrent, painful nodules and abscesses, primarily in areas with apocrine glands. It is not specific to pregnancy and is not classified as a dermatosis of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Common dermatoses of pregnancy include intrahepatic cholestasis, atopic eruption of pregnancy, pruritic urticarial papules and plaques of pregnancy (PUPPP), and pemphigoid gestationis.","Pemphigoid gestationis is an autoimmune blistering disorder that occurs during pregnancy, typically presenting in the second or third trimester."],"references":["Fong M, Gandhi GR, Gharbi A, et al. Pemphigoid Gestationis. [Updated 2024 Feb 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470287/","Sachdeva S. The dermatoses of pregnancy. Indian J Dermatol. 2008;53(3):103-5. doi: 10.4103/0019-5154.43203. PMID: 19882004; PMCID: PMC2763729. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19882004/","S\u00e4vervall C, Sand FL, Thomsen SF. Pemphigoid gestationis: current perspectives. Clin Cosmet Investig Dermatol. 2017 Nov 8;10:441-449. doi: 10.2147/CCID.S128144. PMID: 29184427; PMCID: PMC5685197. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5685197/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2495"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93123"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-06T18:37:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-06T18:37:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111009"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCou